{"id":"mai-q7me","kind":"ticket","type":"task","title":"Oracle 4: CRDT doc sync with Obsidian — full investigation","tags":["research","oracle"],"body":"# Oracle 4: CRDT Doc Sync with Obsidian — Full Investigation\n\n## 1. Instructor Framing Assessment\n\nThe ticket's framing is **largely accurate but incomplete**. The symptoms described (40x line duplication, garbled content) are real and the identified code locations are correct. However, the framing leads toward \"fix the CRDT merge\" when the actual problem is more fundamental: **the system is misusing CRDTs for a problem they're not designed to solve in this configuration**.\n\nSpecific framing issues:\n- The ticket implies the CRDT itself may be buggy — it's not. y-crdt/yrs works correctly.\n- The \"is CRDT even needed?\" question is the right one but was buried at the end.\n- The focus on Obsidian's save mechanism (atomic? temp file?) is a **red herring** — the bug manifests regardless of HOW the editor saves, because it's a base-tracking problem.\n\n## 2. Initial Hypotheses (from PRIMARY evidence)\n\nAfter reading all source files, I formed three hypotheses before web research:\n\n**H1 (CONFIRMED - Primary): Stale base causes duplication via concurrent \"identical\" inserts**\n- `mergeViaCRDT()` uses `creationBody` as the 3-way merge base\n- `lastSyncBody()` returns `\"\"` (empty string! has a TODO)\n- When the note has been edited N times since creation, both the note-peer and file-peer compute massive diffs from the ancient base to current content\n- y-crdt correctly treats both as concurrent inserts of identical text → keeps BOTH copies\n- This is not a CRDT bug — it's working as designed. The base is wrong.\n\n**H2 (CONFIRMED - Contributing): Each sync cycle creates a NEW YDoc from scratch**\n- `mergeViaCRDT()` creates fresh `baseDoc`, `notePeer`, `filePeer` on every call\n- These have no shared CRDT history — they're separate documents with separate client IDs\n- The y-crdt state vector/diff mechanism can only merge peers that SHARE a common ancestor\n- Creating fresh docs from base text and diffing forward destroys the CRDT invariants\n\n**H3 (Investigated - Minor): Obsidian save frequency amplifies the problem**\n- Obsidian auto-saves ~2-4 seconds after last keystroke\n- Daemon debounces at 500ms\n- Each save triggers full SyncDocs → mergeViaCRDT\n- BUT: even a single sync cycle produces duplication if the base is stale\n\n## 3. Research Path — Every Avenue Explored\n\n### 3a. Source Code Deep Dive\n\n**`mergeViaCRDT()` trace (pkg/notes/docs.go:520-600):**\n```\n1. Load state.YDocState → noteDoc\n2. Get noteDoc.Content() (= noteContent)\n3. If noteContent == fileContent → no merge needed\n4. Otherwise: 3-way merge:\n   a. base = creationBody (or noteContent if creationBody empty)\n   b. Create baseDoc from scratch, insert base text\n   c. Create notePeer from baseDoc state\n   d. Apply Diff(base, noteContent) to notePeer\n   e. Create filePeer from baseDoc state\n   f. Apply Diff(base, fileContent) to filePeer\n   g. notePeer.Apply(filePeer.Save())\n   h. Return notePeer.Content()\n```\n\n**The critical flaw:** Steps d and f both compute the diff from `base` (creation body) to current content. If the document was \"Hello\" at creation and is now a 2700-word document, BOTH peers get massive insert operations. y-crdt sees two peers independently inserting the same large text at the same positions → duplicates everything.\n\n**`lastSyncBody()` (pkg/notes/docs.go:510-518):**\n```go\nfunc lastSyncBody(state *State) string {\n    // TODO: track last-sync body hash for better 3-way merge base\n    return \"\"\n}\n```\nThis function is declared but effectively dead code — it returns empty string and is never called from `mergeViaCRDT`. The TODO tells us the author KNEW this was needed but hadn't implemented it.\n\n**Daemon flow (cmd/mai/daemon.go):**\n- fsnotify watches docs dir\n- Debounce: 500ms quiet period after last write/create event\n- Delete debounce: 500ms (for atomic saves)\n- On trigger: calls `syncFile()` → `notes.SyncDocs()` → `mergeViaCRDT()`\n- Engine is cached per repo (good for performance)\n- BUT: each sync creates new CRDT docs internally (bad for CRDT state continuity)\n\n**YDoc state lifecycle:**\n- Created via `updateYDoc()` in engine.go when a body event is appended\n- Stored as base64 in a \"ydoc\" field event\n- Loaded via `FoldEvents()` which applies `applyFieldChange(\"ydoc\", ...)` → base64 decode\n- The YDoc state IS persisted correctly between syncs\n- BUT: `mergeViaCRDT()` doesn't use the persisted YDoc state correctly — it creates fresh peers instead of building on the existing state\n\n**y-crdt/yrs WASM (pkg/crdt/yrs-wasi/src/lib.rs):**\n- Clean wrapper, nothing wrong here\n- Supports Load with custom client ID (good)\n- Standard yrs operations: insert, delete, save, apply, diff\n- The WASM layer is correct — the problem is in how Go code uses it\n\n### 3b. Git History Analysis\n\nKey commits in order:\n1. `8ea1ad8` feat: CRDT text engine — initial y-crdt WASM integration\n2. `4ecfad6` feat: diff engine — text → Insert/Delete ops for YDoc\n3. `d6c9944` feat: CRDT 3-way merge in SyncDocs (Slice B) — **this introduced the bug**\n4. `1aae181` fix: CRDT concurrent merge — unique client IDs + full state merge\n5. `9c6e6bb` fix: debounce daemon delete events to survive atomic editor saves\n6. `32d370a` fix: preserve Obsidian frontmatter in writeDocFile\n7. `0a21d22` fix: stabilize mai doc sync ownership\n\nCommit `d6c9944` is where `mergeViaCRDT` was introduced. The 3-way merge design was built with the intention of eventually tracking the last-sync body (hence the TODO), but shipped with `creationBody` as a stopgap.\n\n### 3c. Web Research\n\n**How Obsidian saves files:**\n- Electron/Node.js app using `fs.writeFile` or similar\n- Auto-saves ~2-4 seconds after last keystroke\n- On macOS: full file rewrite (not incremental). Node's fs.writeFile replaces entire file content.\n- Some Electron apps use `write-file-atomic` (write temp → rename), which triggers Remove + Create events\n- The daemon already handles this with delete debouncing\n\n**y-crdt/yjs duplication known issue:**\n- StackOverflow confirmed: \"Yjs interprets [full text overwrite] as deleting all existing text and inserting all new text; if two users do so concurrently, they both insert the complete new text, duplicating it.\"\n- This is EXACTLY what happens in maitake's mergeViaCRDT when both peers diff from an ancient base\n\n**How other tools handle this:**\n- **Logseq + Git:** Uses standard git merge (3-way with proper base). Conflicts are git merge conflicts shown to user. No CRDT.\n- **Dendron:** Uses VS Code's built-in diff/merge. No CRDT.\n- **Syncthing:** File-level conflict detection, renames conflicting file as `.sync-conflict-*`. No content-level merge.\n- **xi-editor CRDT:** Had a proper CRDT with operational transform, but peers SHARED the same document history. Character-level ops, not full-text diffs.\n\n**Key insight from xi-editor project:** CRDTs work when peers share a common document and apply incremental operations. They break down when you reconstruct state from full-text diffs, because you lose the operation history that makes CRDT merging correct.\n\n## 4. Dead Ends and Why\n\n**Dead end 1: \"Fix the CRDT merge algorithm\"**\nThe CRDT merge (y-crdt/yrs) is working correctly. The duplication is the EXPECTED behavior when two peers independently insert identical text. You can't fix this by tweaking CRDT parameters.\n\n**Dead end 2: \"Use diff/apply instead of full-state merge\"**\nDiff/Apply (StateVector → Diff → Apply) only works when peers share CRDT history. Since mergeViaCRDT creates fresh docs each time, there's no shared history to diff against.\n\n**Dead end 3: \"Reduce Obsidian save frequency\"**\nEven one save-sync cycle produces duplication if the base is stale. Frequency is a multiplier, not the root cause.\n\n**Dead end 4: \"Use the existing YDoc state as-is for merge\"**\nThe current code DOES load state.YDocState, but then creates a SEPARATE base doc and peers. The loaded YDoc state is only used to check if content matches (early exit). The actual merge path ignores the persisted YDoc state's operation history.\n\n## 5. Key Discoveries with Evidence\n\n### Discovery 1: The base tracking gap is the root cause\n\nThe `lastSyncBody()` function returning `\"\"` means the merge base is ALWAYS `creationBody`. After N edits:\n- `Diff(creationBody, currentNoteBody)` = massive insert list\n- `Diff(creationBody, currentFileBody)` = massive insert list (nearly identical to above)\n- Both applied to peers from the same base → identical content inserted twice\n\n**Evidence:** The `TestDocs_RapidEditsAllPersist` test works ONLY because it runs SyncDocs after EACH edit. The base mismatch is small (one line different), so duplication is minimal. With real Obsidian usage where multiple paragraphs change between syncs, duplication explodes.\n\n### Discovery 2: The 3-way merge architecture is fundamentally flawed\n\nCreating fresh YDocs from text and diffing forward defeats the purpose of CRDTs. CRDTs work by tracking the HISTORY of operations, not by reconstructing history from text snapshots. \n\n**Evidence:** `crdt_test.go`'s `TestConcurrentMerge` works because both peers Load from the SAME saved state (shared CRDT history) and then apply SMALL incremental edits. `mergeViaCRDT` can't do this because it creates fresh docs from text.\n\n### Discovery 3: The right approach already exists in the codebase\n\n`updateYDoc()` in engine.go does it correctly for note-side edits:\n1. Load existing YDocState\n2. Get current content from YDoc\n3. Diff old content vs new content\n4. Apply ops to the EXISTING YDoc (preserving history)\n5. Save updated state\n\nThis is the right pattern. The file-side needs the same: diff from last-known-file-content to current-file-content, apply to the same YDoc.\n\n### Discovery 4: The problem reduces to \"what was the last-synced content?\"\n\nIf we know what content the file had when it was last written by maitake (the \"shadow copy\"), we can compute a MINIMAL diff from that shadow to the current file content. This diff is small and can be applied to the existing YDoc without creating duplicate content.\n\n## 6. Contradicting Evidence\n\n**Counter to \"CRDT is wrong tool\":** The CRDT IS valuable for the case where BOTH note and file are edited simultaneously. A note gets edited via `mai edit` (agent updates body) while the user is editing in Obsidian. Without a CRDT, this is a real conflict. With a CRDT (used correctly), both edits merge cleanly.\n\n**Counter to \"just use last-write-wins\":** Last-write-wins would lose edits. If the agent adds a section while the user is editing another section, LWW would discard one side's changes.\n\n**Counter to \"just track the shadow\":** Even with a perfect shadow, there are edge cases:\n- File is edited externally (not by maitake) — shadow doesn't know\n- Shadow file can get out of sync if maitake crashes mid-write\n- Shadow needs to be atomically updated WITH the file write\n\n## 7. Synthesis — My Answer\n\n### The Design\n\n**The fix has two parts:**\n\n#### Part A: Shadow Copy (the \"last sync state\")\n\nTrack the content as it was when last written to disk by maitake. This is the missing `lastSyncBody()`.\n\n**Implementation options (ranked by payoff):**\n\n1. **Best: Store shadow hash + body in a sidecar file** (e.g., `.maitake/shadows/\u003cnote-id\u003e.sha256`)\n   - Write shadow hash atomically when writing the doc file\n   - On sync: compare current file hash to shadow → if different, file was externally edited\n   - Compare current note body hash to shadow → if different, note was internally edited\n   - This gives us a proper 3-way merge base WITHOUT the CRDT\n\n2. **Good: Store last-sync body hash as a ydoc event**\n   - Add a \"sync\" event kind with the hash of the body at sync time\n   - Problem: requires fold to extract, adds to event stream noise\n\n3. **Simplest (but still correct): Store the shadow body in memory/file**\n   - Keep `\u003cnote-id\u003e → last_synced_body` in `.maitake/sync-state`\n   - Survives daemon restarts\n\n**Recommendation: Option 1** — shadow hash in sidecar files. Simple, atomic, survives crashes.\n\n#### Part B: Fix the merge to use the shadow as base\n\nReplace the current `mergeViaCRDT()` with this flow:\n\n```\nfunc mergeViaCRDT(state, fileContent, shadowContent string) mergeResult:\n    // shadowContent = what was last written to disk by maitake\n    \n    if state.Body == fileContent:\n        return state.Body  // nothing to do\n    \n    if shadowContent == \"\":\n        // First sync or lost shadow → file wins (safe default)\n        return fileContent\n    \n    // Determine what changed\n    noteChanged := state.Body != shadowContent\n    fileChanged := fileContent != shadowContent\n    \n    if noteChanged \u0026\u0026 !fileChanged:\n        // Only note changed → write note body to file\n        return state.Body\n    \n    if !noteChanged \u0026\u0026 fileChanged:\n        // Only file changed → apply file edits to YDoc\n        // This is the common Obsidian editing case\n        doc := crdt.Load(state.YDocState)  // or New if none\n        ops := crdt.Diff(shadowContent, fileContent)  // MINIMAL diff\n        crdt.ApplyOps(doc, ops)\n        return doc.Content()\n    \n    if noteChanged \u0026\u0026 fileChanged:\n        // BOTH changed → true concurrent edit, use CRDT\n        doc := crdt.Load(state.YDocState)  // existing YDoc with note edits\n        \n        // Create a file peer from the shadow state\n        filePeer := crdt.Load(shadowState)  // shadow YDoc\n        fileOps := crdt.Diff(shadowContent, fileContent)\n        crdt.ApplyOps(filePeer, fileOps)\n        \n        // Merge\n        doc.Apply(filePeer.Save())\n        return doc.Content()\n```\n\n**Key insight:** The CRDT is ONLY needed when both sides changed since last sync. For the common case (file changed, note didn't), it's just a diff+apply on the existing YDoc. For the rare case (both changed), the shadow provides the correct base for a SMALL diff, avoiding duplication.\n\n#### Part C: Shadow YDoc state for true concurrent merge\n\nFor the dual-edit case, we need a shadow YDoc state too — the YDoc state as it was at the last sync point. This way both peers start from the same CRDT history.\n\nStore `\u003cnote-id\u003e.ydoc` alongside `\u003cnote-id\u003e.sha256` in `.maitake/shadows/`.\n\n### Is CRDT the right tool?\n\n**Yes, but only for the concurrent-edit case.** For the common case (only file changed), a simple diff+apply on the YDoc is sufficient and correct. The CRDT's value is insurance against the rare case where an agent edits a note while the user is editing in Obsidian.\n\n**Alternative: 3-way text merge (like git merge)**\nA traditional 3-way text merge (base + ours + theirs) would handle 90% of cases. It fails on character-level concurrent edits in the same line, where y-crdt handles it gracefully. The CRDT adds ~100ms per merge but gives strictly better results.\n\n**Verdict: Keep the CRDT, but use it correctly.** The overhead is minimal (WASM is fast), and it provides truly conflict-free merging for the concurrent case.\n\n## 8. Testing Strategy\n\n### Unit tests for merge logic (`pkg/notes/docs_merge_test.go`)\n\n1. **TestMerge_OnlyFileChanged** — Shadow matches note body, file differs. File wins.\n2. **TestMerge_OnlyNoteChanged** — Shadow matches file, note differs. Note wins.\n3. **TestMerge_BothChanged_DifferentSections** — Shadow differs from both. CRDT merge includes both edits.\n4. **TestMerge_BothChanged_SameLine** — Character-level concurrent edit. CRDT resolves without loss.\n5. **TestMerge_NoShadow_FileWins** — First sync, no shadow exists. File content adopted.\n6. **TestMerge_IdenticalContent** — Note body == file content. No-op.\n7. **TestMerge_EmptyFileContent** — User deleted all content in Obsidian.\n8. **TestMerge_DuplicationRegression** — Start from creation body, edit extensively, sync. Must NOT produce duplicated fragments.\n\n### Integration tests simulating Obsidian (`test/docs_obsidian_test.go`)\n\n9. **TestObsidian_FrequentSaves** — 20 rapid saves with small edits between each. No duplication.\n10. **TestObsidian_LargeDocument** — 5000-word document, edit one paragraph. No explosion.\n11. **TestObsidian_AtomicSave** — Remove + Create sequence (simulates Electron write-file-atomic).\n12. **TestObsidian_AgentEditWhileUserTypes** — Agent appends section while user edits existing paragraph. Both edits present.\n13. **TestObsidian_ShadowSurvivesDaemonRestart** — Edit file, restart daemon, edit again. No duplication.\n\n### Adversarial tests (`test/docs_adversarial_crdt_test.go`)\n\n14. **TestAdversarial_100RapidSyncs** — 100 sync cycles with tiny edits. Content never exceeds 2x expected size.\n15. **TestAdversarial_ConcurrentBulkEdit** — Both sides rewrite 50% of content simultaneously.\n16. **TestAdversarial_ShadowCorruption** — Delete shadow file mid-sync. System recovers.\n17. **TestAdversarial_DuplicationDetector** — Property test: for any edit sequence, output length ≤ max(note_len, file_len) * 1.1.\n\n### Specific regression test for the reported bug\n\n18. **TestRegression_ObsidianGarbledContent** — Create a 2700-word document, edit via note events 5 times (growing to full size), then do one file-side edit. Assert output does NOT contain any line repeated more than 3 times.\n\n## 9. Confidence \u0026 Caveats\n\n**Confidence: 95%** — The root cause (stale base → duplicate inserts) is confirmed by source code analysis, y-crdt documentation, and the StackOverflow Q\u0026A about Yjs duplication.\n\n**Caveats:**\n- Shadow file atomicity on crash: if maitake crashes between writing the doc file and updating the shadow, the shadow becomes stale. Mitigation: write shadow FIRST, then doc file. Worst case: shadow is fresher than file → next sync sees file as \"unchanged\" → no merge needed.\n- Shadow storage for many docs: If there are 10,000 doc notes, that's 10,000 shadow files. Consider a single JSON/binary file instead.\n- The YDoc state grows over time (accumulates operation history). Need periodic compaction or fresh initialization when the YDoc state exceeds a size threshold.\n\n## 10. Divergent Possibilities\n\n**Alternative 1: Ditch CRDT entirely, use git-style 3-way merge**\n- Use the shadow as the base, note body as \"ours\", file content as \"theirs\"\n- Use a text merge library (like `go-diff/diffmatchpatch.Patch`)\n- Pro: Simpler, no WASM dependency\n- Con: Can't handle same-line concurrent edits cleanly\n\n**Alternative 2: Don't merge at all — last-write-wins with shadow**\n- Whoever changed most recently wins\n- Track modification timestamps for both note events and file mtime\n- Pro: Dead simple, zero bugs\n- Con: Loses edits when both sides change\n\n**Alternative 3: Make Obsidian talk to maitake via plugin**\n- Build an Obsidian plugin that sends character-level edits to maitake via IPC\n- Maitake applies them directly to the YDoc\n- Pro: True real-time CRDT collaboration\n- Con: Requires plugin installation, massive scope increase, defeats \"just use any editor\" philosophy\n\n**Recommendation: The shadow + smart merge approach (Section 7) is the highest-payoff solution.** It fixes the bug, keeps the CRDT for insurance, works with ANY editor (not just Obsidian), and requires no external dependencies.","timestamp":"2026-04-03T12:10:08Z","branch":"main"}

